<!--- Categories ---> [[Category:Virtual communities]] [[Category:Internet culture]] [[Category:Technology in society]] [[Category:Virtual reality]] [[Category:Community building]] [[Category:Social information processing]] [[Category:Community websites]] [[Category:Social software]] [[Category:Articles created via the Article Wizard]]

The '''Geek Pride Festival''' was the name of a number of events between 1998 and 2000, organized by [[Tim McEachern]] and devoted to computer [[geek]] activities and interests. The name of the festival is most often associated with the large event held on March 31 and April 1, 2000 at the Park Plaza Castle in [[Boston]], United States.
Before that there were two events at the now closed Big House Brewery in [[Albany, New York]]. [http://www.wamc.org WAMC], the local NPR affiliate, sponsored the events which were organized by Tim McEachern.
==2000 event== {{Tone|date=November 2008}} [[Image:Geek pride festival t-shirt.png|thumb|right|Geek Pride Festival T-shirt]] The 2000 event was a major production, organized with the help of [[Susan Kaup]], Chris O'Brien and many volunteers.
The event began Friday night, with a swap meet / social event at the Modern Lounge in Boston's [[Landsdowne Street]] nightclub district. Drink tickets were offered at the door, and the DJ played computer-themed music (e.g., ''[[It's All About The Pentiums]]'').
On Saturday, the main event occurred at the Castle, where admission was free. The middle of the floor held the "Email Garden", comprising about a dozen tables with [[Personal computer|PC]]s running [[Red Hat Linux]], in a wired [[LAN]] network and providing [[email]], [[World Wide Web|Web]], and general [[Internet]] access. At the front of the hall was a stage, which hosted a number of invited guests, including [[Rob Malda]] of [[Slashdot]], [[Eric S. Raymond]], the [[video game]] cover band [[Everyone (band)|Everyone]]. The stage was also host to the final round of a [[Quake III]] tournament, held in a back room, displayed on the stage's projection screen, as well as the final round of "Stump the Geek", a geek [[trivia]] contest.
Aside from the main events, the main floor had computer workstations displaying live [[webcam]] feeds of "satellite" Festivals in remote locations. A live [[Shoutcast]] feed was also provided of the Boston event. A poll for "greatest geek hero" was also held; the official winner was [[Alan Turing]].<ref>[http://everything.blockstackers.com/index.pl?node_id=475132]</ref>
According to Science/AAAS magazine, 2,000 people attended, though the open-door free admission made an official count impossible.{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}}
===Corporate sponsors=== *[[VA Linux]] (now [[SourceForge, Inc.]]) *[[Andover.net]] ( now [[OSTG]], part of SourceForge) *SwitcHouse (now [[Nintari]]) *[[Addison-Wesley]]
===Speakers=== *[[Alex Pentland]] *[[Rob Malda]] *Keith Dawson, editor of ''[[Tasty Bits from the Technology Front]]'' *[[Eric S. Raymond]] *''[[The Cluetrain Manifesto]]'' authors [[Christopher Locke]] & [[David Weinberger]] *Micky Metts aka [Michele D. Metts] *[[Jeffrey Zeldman]] *[[Dave Green (journalist)|Dave Green]] & [[Danny O'Brien (journalist)|Danny O'Brien]] of UK based ntk.net
==Other events== The 2000 event is widely referred to as the "first annual" event, although McEachern organized at least one previous event named Geek Pride Festival (and/or Geek Pride Day) at a bar in Albany, New York. Some sources refer to the Boston event as the ''third'' annual.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}
McEachern planned another event to take place later the same year in [[San Francisco]], but was never realized.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}
==References== *{{cite web |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/TECH/computing/04/04/proud.geeks.idg/index.html |title=We're geeks and we're proud |last=Gouthro |first=Liane |date=4 April 2000 |publisher=CNN.com |accessdate=7 December 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070913190214/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/TECH/computing/04/04/proud.geeks.idg/index.html |archivedate=13 September 2007 |df= }}
