{{redirect|Nizkor|text=See also [[Equipo Nizkor]], a human rights organisation mainly concerned with Latin America, and [[Bereavement in Judaism#Yizkor|Yizkor]], a Jewish prayer and symbolic word}} {{Multiple issues| {{Refimprove|date=May 2015}} {{One source|date=May 2015}} }} {{Infobox website | name = Nizkor Project | logo = | logocaption = | screenshot = | collapsible = | collapsetext = | caption = | url = {{URL|www.nizkor.org|Nizkor.org}} | slogan = | commercial = | type = [[Educational]], [[anti-fascism]] | registration = | language = English | num_users = | content_license = | programming_language = | owner = B'nai Brith Canada | author = | editor = | launch_date = <!-- {{start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} --> | revenue = | alexa = <!-- {{increase}} {{steady}} {{decrease}} [http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/example.com ##] (US/Global MM/YYYY) --> | ip = | current_status = | footnotes = }}
The '''Nizkor Project''' ({{lang-he|נִזְכּוֹר}}, "we will remember") is an [[Internet]]-based project run by [[B'nai Brith Canada]] which is dedicated to countering [[Holocaust denial]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Nizkor Project|url=http://fighthatred.com/522/the-nizkor-project/|work=Fight Hatred|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref>
==About the project== The website was founded by [[Kenneth McVay|Ken McVay]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Community Directory - The Nizkor Project|url=http://www.mvjf.org/IR/community-directory.aspx?id=3025&category=637|accessdate=28 September 2013}}</ref> as a central Web-based archive for the large numbers of documents made publicly available by the users of the newsgroup ''alt.revisionism'' and gifted to B'nai Brith Canada in 2010.{{Citation needed|date=May 2015}}
The site also archives numerous postings made to the newsgroup since the early 1990s. It does not archive every single posting ever made to the newsgroup; rather, the maintainers of the web site have selected various messages for display that are seen as presenting factual information about [[the Holocaust]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Nizkor Project holocaust web crawler|url=http://www.writing.upenn.edu/~afilreis/Holocaust/nizkor-search.html|publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania]]|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> or, in the case of some posters, about the authors of the messages themselves.{{Citation needed|date=May 2015}}
In addition to providing an extensive archive of documents regarding the Holocaust, including the transcripts of the 1st Nuremberg Tribunal,<ref>{{cite web|title=The International Military Tribunal Nuremberg|url=http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/imt/|work=Nizkor|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> the Nizkor Project also seeks to expose the activities of Holocaust deniers themselves.<ref>{{cite news|title=Newslink|url=http://edition.cnn.com/almanac/9605/10/|accessdate=16 February 2014|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=May 10, 1996}}</ref> Based on the postings to the newsgroup over the years, it has compiled extensive writings from self-proclaimed revisionists, including [[David Irving]],<ref>{{cite web|title=David Irving|url=http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/i/irving-david/|work=Nizkor|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> [[Ernst Zündel]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Ernst Zündel|url=http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/z/zundel-ernst/|work=Nizkor|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> [[Michael A. Hoffman II]], and others. Among the various pieces of information stored at Nizkor is a sound recording of an [[answering machine]] message allegedly made by [[white supremacist]] [[Tom Metzger (white supremacist)|Tom Metzger]], encouraging various individuals to "take action" against "Zinkor {{sic}} on the Internet."<ref>{{cite web|title=W.A.R. Targets Nizkor|url=http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/orgs/american/war/war-targets-nizkor.html|work=Nizkor Project|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref>
In 2009, the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] congratulated the NIZKOR who was one of those that initiated the effort that lead to the successful prosecution of three NAZI war criminal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=5711841&ct=7499875|title=Wiesenthal Center Praises Indictment by Spanish Court of Three Nazi War Criminals Denaturalized and Ordered Deported From the United States - Simon Wiesenthal Center|publisher=}}</ref>
===Criticisms=== Holocaust denial Web sites and spokespersons have made repeated accusations against McVay, challenging his neutrality and attacking him personally.<ref>{{cite web|title=How much of Nizkor's material is truth?|url=http://codoh.com/library/document/1056|work=codoh|accessdate=28 September 2013}}</ref> The Nizkor web site has been accused by self-proclaimed "Holocaust revisionists" and [[neo-Nazi]] Web sites as being funded by [[Israel]] and other [[Zionism|Zionist]] sources, though McVay consistently denies these charges. He states that the Nizkor Project is funded solely by donations from the general public, as well as his own personal finances.{{Citation needed|date=May 2015}}
In the late 1990s, the Simon Wiesenthal Center criticized the Nizkor Project for increasing the visibility of hate groups and Holocaust deniers, even as it sought to debunk them.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Littman Letter|url=http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/l/littman-sol/littman-letter.html|work=Nizkor|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> This debate between [[free speech]] advocates such as McVay and those who favor the suppression of speech with [[hate crime]] laws continued throughout the late 1990s, but has now mostly been resolved with the two sides agreeing on the common goal of confronting holocaust deniers and keeping their disagreements over specific tactics private. In 1996, McVay spoke out against Internet hate crime laws in Canada in front of a committee of the Canadian Parliament, stating that it is better to address the false claims of Holocaust deniers, rather than to censor them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/35/Archives/committees352/huso/evidence/05_96-04-30/huso-05-cover-e.html |title=Committee Evidence, House of Commons of Canada}}</ref>
